Chueh  Aminomethylation of heliomycin: preparation and anticancer characterization of the first  series of semi-synthetic derivatives  A series of 4-aminomethyl derivatives of heliomycin 1 was prepared using the Mannich reaction.  The  modification  significantly  improved  aqueous  solubility  of  the  initially  poorly  soluble  antibiotic. Testing the antiproliferative efficacy revealed a potent activity of heliomycin as well  as its new derivatives on a panel of mammalian tumor cells including drug resistant variants. In  contrast  to  1  the  new  derivatives  7a,  7l,  7p  generated  a  high  level  of  ROS  associated  with

induction  of  apoptosis  in  T24  bladder  cancer  cells.  Introduction  of  4-aminomethyl  moiety  increased  the  affinity  to  DNA  and  the  ability  to  inhibit  topoisomerase  1  making  7p  the  most  promising  candidate  for  further  preclinical  evaluation.  Thus,  aminomethylation  is  the  first-in- class  successful  transformation  of  the  antibiotic  1  resulting  in  an  improved  water  solubility  of  derivatives and promising properties in search of novel anticancer drug candidates.  Keywords: heliomycin, resistomycin, Mannich aminomethylation, anticancer agents, DNA, ROS,  The chemical modification of heliomycin via Mannich aminomethylation was developed.  17 new derivatives with improved water solubility were synthesized.  Heliomycin and its new derivatives inhibit growth of tumor cell lines including resistant variants. This approach allowed to diversify  the  structure  of  1  and,  for  the  first  time,  to  prepare  a  series  of  4-aminomethyl  derivatives  with  significantly improved aqueous solubility. Compound 1 and the majority  of its new derivatives  demonstrated  a  potent  (at  submicromolar  or  low  micromolar  concentrations)  antiproliferative  effect against a panel of mammalian tumor cell lines. Furthermore, the compounds were capable  of  circumventing  two  mechanisms  of  drug  resistance,  that  is,  Pgp  expression  and  p53  inactivation.  Despite  the  fact  that  the  cytotoxic  effect  of  7a-q  is  comparable  with  the  paternal  antibiotic  1,  our  modification  substantially  increased  water  solubility  of  the  derivatives  of  this  Application  of  the  Mannich  aminomethylation  was  discovered  as  a  powerful  way  for  cells  and  intracellular  targets.  Introduction  of  the  substituted  aminomethyl  moiety  at  the  4- position of 1 increased the binding to the DNA duplex. Moreover, an additional amino group in  4-(4-aminopiperidine-1-yl)methyl derivative 7p provided the highest affinity to DNA as well as  potent inhibition of Top1. In contrast to 1, all 4-aminomethyl derivatives 7a, 7l, and 7p exhibited

the  ability  to  bind  DNA  duplex,  to  inhibit  Top  1  and  to  trigger  apoptosis  that  correlated  with  their  ability  to  generate  ROS.  In  this  regards,  it  is  proposed  that  ROS  production  and/or  Top1  inhibition  are  major  mechanisms  thereby  the  new  aminomethylated  heliomycin  derivatives  induce  tumor  cell  death.  Overall,  we  for  the  first  time  reported  a  successful  transformation  of  heliomycin to improve its solubility and efficiently modulate the biological activities of tentative  novel  therapeutic  candidates.  In  particular,  the  derivative  7p  bearing  4-(4-aminopiperidine-1- yl)methyl moiety is perspective for an in-depth evaluation.
